Passing XPathConstants.NODE does not cause `evaluate` to return a NodeList, it causes the method to return a single Node.  The [class documentation](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/9/docs/api/javax/xml/xpath/XPathConstants.html) describes exactly what type of object will be returned for each XPathConstant field.

    Node node = (Node) xPath.evaluate(&quot;DIAttribute[@name=&#39;ui_display_name&#39;]&quot;, element, XPathConstants.NODE);

Attributes are document nodes too, so you can simplify the code into a single XPath expression:

    Node node = (Node) xPath.evaluate(&quot;DIAttribute[@name=&#39;ui_display_name&#39;]/@value&quot;, element, XPathConstants.NODE);
    String name = node.getNodeValue();

Since you just want the string value of the node, you can use the [two-argument evaluate method](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/9/docs/api/javax/xml/xpath/XPath.html#evaluate-java.lang.String-java.lang.Object-) instead, omitting the XPathConstants value:

    String name = xPath.evaluate(&quot;DIAttribute[@name=&#39;ui_display_name&#39;]/@value&quot;, element);

That will only find DIAttribute elements which are direct children of `element`.  If you want to search all DIAttribute descendants at all levels below `element`, use `.//` in your XPath expression:

    String name = xPath.evaluate(&quot;.//DIAttribute[@name=&#39;ui_display_name&#39;]/@value&quot;, element);

